result.execSummary:
The defendant Joshua J Hansen was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/Intent-THC (<=200 grams) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(h)1.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Consecutive to: to any other sentence. FORTHWITH. Credit for 4 days time served. The first 21 days will be served in custody without release privileges. After this initial period of incarceration, if defendant has no major rules violations, and isaccepted into the Day Reporting Program, defendant may serve the balance of his sentence with release privileges to attend the Day Reporting Program. The Court has no objection to the Defendant being placed on Electronic Monitoring while participating in the program. Should the Defendant violate either conditions of Electronic Monitoring or the rules at the Day Reporting Program the Defendant will serve the balance of said sentence without release privileges. Possession or use of any illegal controlled substance or alcohol forfeits the Huber (work release) privileges and any referral of reporting time.

COURT ORDERED THE FOLLOWING CONDITIONS:
No new law violations reaching the level of a probable cause finding. MUST provide a DNA sample to the State Crime Lab, if you have not previously done so. DNA Sample 973.046 & 973.047. Defendant cannot vote in any election until your civil rights are restored. 973.176(2).
Pay costs, surcharges, assessments, supervision and DNA fees on or before 7-01-15. Failure to pay shall result in a Civil Judgment with tax intercept.
ABSOLUTE SOBRIETY.  AODA assessment and treatment. Random urine screens.

As a convicted felon Defendant shall NEVER be in possess of any firearms 941.29 Wis. Stats. makes it another felony for anyone who has been convicted of a felony to ever possess a firearm, carrying with it its own 10 year period of imprisonment or $25,000 fine or both. Possess Weapon as Convicted Felon 973.176(1).

Defendant Joshua J Hansen in court with Chelsea Brocker, student, with attorney Melissa J Fitzsimmons.  William Levins appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Clerk;ds

Motion to suppress due to stop and Goodchild motion proceeds.  Sworn-in for the State:  Village of Greendale Detective Robert Windler; Exhibit #1 marked, identified, offered and received into evidence.  State rests subject to rebuttal.  Sworn-in for the defense:  Joshua Hansen.  Defense rests.  State rests.  Testimony closed.  Arguments by counsel.  Court finds the detective's version of events more credible; the detective did have a reasonable and articulable suspicion to stop the vehicle and the defendant would have been discovered through the telephone.  As to the statement:  Court finds the detective more credible; the statement was freely and voluntarily made and not the result of undue pressure.  Motion for suppression is denies.  Pre-trial conference scheduled for May 30, 2014 at 08:30 am.
